I believe they've covered it in bits and pieces in other videos similar to this one. Botox obviously restricts muscles, making it harder to read expressions in the affected areas, but it's not the case of completely freezing a person's entire face. An observer/analyser of body language would establish a baseline with the subject so they can still spot deviations in behaviour and look to the cues that are still visible in these cases:

Facial expression, indicators around the moving muscles as these still operate the same way. Eye movement is not affected by botox and can be a clear marker under pressure, including where they look and when, and movement of the head (up, down, to the side, do they jut in towards the interrogator or pull away)
Hands and arms and shoulders, do they close or cross them to make a pdychological barrier or open them up to imply honesty and trust, do they use illustrators and why
Body position, leaning in or away
Speech pattern and choice of language, particularly, does it match the emotion they are displaying or does it appear to be creating a false narrative.
There are other cues to look for as well in body language, such as stress responses like tapping or rubbing of the hands and shaking legs or feet, and one this channel taught me with the Prince Andrew video, which is detecting a person's heart rate by having them pop one knee on top of the other to see how their hanging foot bobs as blood comes through the artery.

When you consider all these factors are still relevant in examining a subject, botox does create a degree of extra challenge if you can't see a person's body, particularly when looking at a video, but if you had any idea what you were doing as an interrogator you would adjust the scene so that you can examine an entire body to be able to spot markers across the entire body.
